1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,217
Every time you chat with a large language model,

2
00:00:04,217 --> 00:00:07,967
a silent computational storm rages inside the GPU.

3
00:00:07,967 --> 00:00:11,247
In autoregressive decoding, the model generates text

4
00:00:11,247 --> 00:00:13,590
one word at a time.

5
00:00:13,590 --> 00:00:18,277
But here is the catch: to generate the next token,

6
00:00:18,277 --> 00:00:21,558
the model needs to attend to every

7
00:00:21,558 --> 00:00:24,370
single token that came before it.

8
00:00:24,370 --> 00:00:27,650
If we recalculated all self-attention matrices from

9
00:00:27,650 --> 00:00:32,337
scratch at every step, the processing latency would scale quadratically,

10
00:00:32,337 --> 00:00:35,149
grinding generation to a painful halt.

11
00:00:35,149 --> 00:00:38,898
To solve this, modern engines use the Key-Value,

12
00:00:38,898 --> 00:00:42,178
or KV, Cache to store historical context.

13
00:00:42,178 --> 00:00:46,865
Today, we will demystify the mechanics of KV Cache Optimization,

14
00:00:46,865 --> 00:00:51,551
exploring how MQA, GQA, and PagedAttention conquered the memory wall.

15
00:00:51,551 --> 00:00:54,607
While the KV Cache prevents redundant computations,

16
00:00:54,607 --> 00:00:58,100
it introduces a brutal physical bottleneck: memory capacity.

17
00:00:58,100 --> 00:01:01,156
The size of the KV Cache is

18
00:01:01,156 --> 00:01:05,085
not trivial; it scales linearly with the batch size,

19
00:01:05,085 --> 00:01:09,451
sequence length, model depth, and the number of attention heads.

20
00:01:09,451 --> 00:01:12,507
Mathematically, the memory footprint in bytes equals

21
00:01:12,507 --> 00:01:14,690
two times the batch size,

22
00:01:14,690 --> 00:01:18,619
times the sequence length, times the number of layers,

23
00:01:18,619 --> 00:01:20,802
times the number of heads,

24
00:01:20,802 --> 00:01:24,731
times the head dimension, times the bytes per parameter.

25
00:01:24,731 --> 00:01:27,787
For a Llama-two seventy-billion parameter model running

26
00:01:27,787 --> 00:01:30,843
a batch of one hundred and twenty-eight

27
00:01:30,843 --> 00:01:34,772
sequences at a context window of four thousand tokens,

28
00:01:34,772 --> 00:01:37,828
this cache alone consumes over one hundred

29
00:01:37,828 --> 00:01:40,447
and twenty gigabytes of high-bandwidth memory.

30
00:01:40,447 --> 00:01:43,940
This causes GPUs to run out of memory,

31
00:01:43,940 --> 00:01:46,559
or OOM, limiting throughput and concurrency.

32
00:01:46,560 --> 00:01:51,632
To alleviate this memory pressure, researchers looked at attention head architecture.

33
00:01:51,632 --> 00:01:53,937
Standard Multi-Head Attention, or MHA,

34
00:01:53,937 --> 00:01:59,010
assigns a unique key and value head to every query head.

35
00:01:59,010 --> 00:02:01,315
To compress this, Multi-Query Attention,

36
00:02:01,315 --> 00:02:04,543
or MQA, uses a single key and

37
00:02:04,543 --> 00:02:07,771
value head shared across all query heads.

38
00:02:07,771 --> 00:02:10,999
While this reduces the cache size by

39
00:02:10,999 --> 00:02:14,226
up to eight times, it can degrade

40
00:02:14,226 --> 00:02:18,376
model accuracy because of the drastic loss in capacity.

41
00:02:18,376 --> 00:02:22,065
The elegant middle-ground is Grouped-Query Attention, or GQA.

42
00:02:22,065 --> 00:02:24,832
GQA partitions query heads into groups,

43
00:02:24,832 --> 00:02:29,443
with each group sharing a single key and value head.

44
00:02:29,443 --> 00:02:32,671
For instance, an eight-to-one ratio allows GQA

45
00:02:32,671 --> 00:02:35,899
to achieve almost the same speed and

46
00:02:35,899 --> 00:02:39,127
memory savings as MQA, while fully maintaining

47
00:02:39,127 --> 00:02:42,816
the high quality and accuracy of Multi-Head Attention.

48
00:02:42,816 --> 00:02:45,479
But even with head compression,

49
00:02:45,479 --> 00:02:50,274
we face another massive inefficiency: how memory is allocated.

50
00:02:50,274 --> 00:02:54,003
Standard engines pre-allocate contiguous memory blocks for

51
00:02:54,003 --> 00:02:56,666
the maximum possible sequence length.

52
00:02:56,666 --> 00:02:59,330
Since most requests finish early,

53
00:02:59,330 --> 00:03:03,059
this results in up to sixty percent

54
00:03:03,059 --> 00:03:08,919
of the pre-allocated memory being wasted—a classic case of internal fragmentation.

55
00:03:08,919 --> 00:03:14,778
To solve this, PagedAttention adapts virtual memory techniques from operating systems.

56
00:03:14,778 --> 00:03:20,105
It divides the KV Cache of each sequence into small,

57
00:03:20,105 --> 00:03:21,704
fixed-size physical blocks.

58
00:03:21,704 --> 00:03:25,433
Instead of contiguous allocation, physical blocks are

59
00:03:25,433 --> 00:03:29,162
mapped dynamically using a logical-to-physical block table.

60
00:03:29,162 --> 00:03:32,891
This allows non-contiguous storage, eliminates internal fragmentation,

61
00:03:32,891 --> 00:03:36,620
and enables different sequences to safely share

62
00:03:36,620 --> 00:03:42,480
key and value blocks, multiplying concurrency by up to four times.

63
00:03:42,480 --> 00:03:46,808
By co-designing attention head architectures and operating-system-style memory managers,

64
00:03:46,808 --> 00:03:52,098
GQA and PagedAttention have redefined the efficiency frontier of deep learning.

65
00:03:52,098 --> 00:03:55,464
They allow us to run larger models,

66
00:03:55,464 --> 00:03:58,830
handle massive context windows, and serve thousands

67
00:03:58,830 --> 00:04:03,159
of concurrent users without changing the model's underlying weights.

68
00:04:03,159 --> 00:04:06,525
If you want to keep mastering the

69
00:04:06,525 --> 00:04:09,411
engineering breakthroughs shaping modern artificial intelligence,

70
00:04:09,411 --> 00:04:14,701
hit the subscribe button for Gemini three point five Flash Model.

71
00:04:14,701 --> 00:04:17,586
Let's push the boundaries of performance,

72
00:04:17,586 --> 00:04:20,471
one physical block at a time.
